body:
After playing with the code I see what our misunderstandings are. So let me try to clarify things.

a) I want to use a visitor to calculate a metric `m`.
b) The visitor implements one of the visit methods, for instance the [visitCtMethod](https://github.com/INRIA/spoon/blob/master/src/main/java/spoon/reflect/visitor/CtVisitor.java#L293).
c) Within this visit method, I would like to initialize `m` with a value, for instance 0, **before** the `CtMethod` is processed. By processing an element I mean applying the recursive descent.
d) Now the recursive descent starts.
e) In order to calculate `m` my visitor implements other visit methods as well, for instance [visitCtReturn](https://github.com/INRIA/spoon/blob/master/src/main/java/spoon/reflect/visitor/CtVisitor.java#L350).
f) If the method mentioned in e) gets called `m` is updated (for example by incrementing `m`) .
g) At some point the element mentioned in c) (our method element) has been processed. That is, all its children have been visited. I would like to have a function which behaves like a `postVisit`, `afterVisit`, `endVisit`, or whatever you would like to name it. JDT, for instance, provides [this](http://help.eclipse.org/luna/topic/org.eclipse.jdt.doc.isv/reference/api/org/eclipse/jdt/core/dom/ASTVisitor.html#endVisit-org.eclipse.jdt.core.dom.MethodDeclaration-) method. This method allows me to grab `m` and use it in further calculations.

So what do I need. I need a visit function that definitely gets called **before** processing and a visit function that definitely gets called **after** processing.

My suggestion is to extend the `CtVisitor` interface providing the functions `beforeVisit...` and `afterVisit...` for each `visit` method. Afterwards, the `ProcessingVisitor` makes usage of these methods by extending the `scan` method:

``` java
    @Override
    @SuppressWarnings("unchecked")
    public void scan(CtElement e) {
        if (e == null) {
            return;
        }

               // call the beforeVisit method of e

        Processor<CtElement> p = (Processor<CtElement>) processor;
        if (p.getTraversalStrategy() == TraversalStrategy.PRE_ORDER
                && canBeProcessed(p, e)) {
            if (p.isToBeProcessed(e)) {
                p.process(e);
            }
        }
        super.scan(e);
        if (p.getTraversalStrategy() == TraversalStrategy.POST_ORDER
                && canBeProcessed(p, e)) {
            if (p.isToBeProcessed(e)) {
                p.process(e);
            }
        }

                // call the afterVisit method of e
    }
```

Ok, I think I understand what do you want (I hope...) and what do you want to do can be done with a subclass of a `CtScanner` like this one:

``` java
public class MetricScanner extends CtScanner {
    Map<CtMethod, Integer> metrics = new HashMap<CtMethod, Integer>();

    @Override
    public <T> void visitCtMethod(CtMethod<T> m) {
        // Before visiting the content of the method.
        metrics.put(m, 0);

        super.visitCtMethod(m);

        // After visiting the method.
        // TODO Do stuff.
    }

    @Override
    public <R> void visitCtReturn(CtReturn<R> returnStatement) {
        // Before visiting the content of the return.
        // TODO Do stuff.

        super.visitCtReturn(returnStatement);

        // After visiting the content of the return.
        // TODO Do stuff.
    }

    @Override
    public <T> void visitCtInvocation(CtInvocation<T> invocation) {
        CtExecutable<T> target = invocation.getExecutable().getDeclaration();
        if (metrics.containsKey(target)) {
            metrics.put((CtMethod) target, metrics.get(target) + 1);
        }

        super.visitCtInvocation(invocation);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Launcher launcher = new Launcher();
        // Initialize launcher...
        launcher.buildModel();

        new MetricScanner().scan(launcher.getFactory().Package().getRootPackage());
    }
}
```
